recordings.file-name: CAPE MAY WARBLER flight call Palmyra NJ 92906.mp3

recordings.rmk: This is an audio extract (converted, amplified and edited) from a video recording of a series of high, thin chip calls that seem to match both to the ear and to the sonogram for Cape May Warbler, though this needs confirmation.  The calls start right away (within 1 sec.), and have been isolated from the other species in the original recording by editing.  This can be compared to the original at XC619854, where the calls are heard in their original context among other sps.  Further ID comment is requested.

This is an audio extract (converted, amplified) from a video recording of a series of high, thin chip calls that seem to match both to the ear and to the sonogram for Cape May Warbler, though this needs confirmation.  The calls start right away (within 1 sec.), and continue throughout at about 1.5-2 sec. intervals, not to be confused with the occasional California Towhee calls, the first of which is heard right after the first chip of interest here.  These higher chips were heard from an unseen bird calling from the crown of a tall oak tree along a freshwater slough near a lake.  The calls have an especially high pitch (8-9 KHz) in a narrow band, with the cadence and modulation that appear a very good match to known recordings for this species, such as  XC319513 - Cape May Warbler - Setophaga tigrina on this site.  However, further comparison and comment is invited.  So far, despite comparison with a number of other species (various warblers, Song Sparrow, kinglets, creeper), this seems to be the best match, but other opinions will be welcomed, and this will be put up for forum discussion.  Location map is a close approximation, though hand placed.
